Ensemble Techniques Project

Submitted by Utathya Ghosh

Batch - AIML Online Jan 21-A

PROJECT BASED
¶

TOTAL SCORE - 60
¶

DOMAIN: Telecom

CONTEXT: A telecom company wants to use their historical customer data to predict behaviour to retain customers. You can analyse all relevant customer data and develop focused customer retention programs.

DATA DESCRIPTION: Each row represents a customer, each column contains customers attributes described on the column Metadata. The data set includes information about:

  1. Customers who left within the last month the column is called Churn
  2. Services that each customer has signed up for phone, multiple lines, internet, online security, online backup, device protection, tech support, and streaming TV and movies
  3. Customer account information how long theyve been a customer, contract, payment method, paperless billing, monthly charges, and total charges
  4. Demographic info about customers gender, age range, and if they have partners and dependents

PROJECT OBJECTIVE: Build a model that will help to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability to churn. This help the company to understand the pinpoints and patterns of customer churn and will increase the focus on strategising customer retention.

Please note that due to multiple grid search in the code, running the entire notebook will take close to an hour, or more depending on the system. I thought about adding if conditions on certain steps in case the auditor wishes to skip the Grid Search steps but that caused some cosmetic issues. Hence I suggest that the auditor jump Grid Search steps on their own in case they want to run the entire notebook and also do it fast.

for t in range(5,30,5):
# Running a loop through all variables
    try:
        for name in vars().keys():
            # Entry into loop allowed only for dataframes created based on our naming conventions
            if name[:3] == "df_":
                # Printing Required informations
                print(name, ":-")
                print("Shape : ", eval(name).shape)
                print("Size : ", eval(name).size)
                # Extra print added for cosmetic reasons
                print()
        break
    except RuntimeError as e:
        time.sleep(t)
        continue

• Automate all the above steps¶
In [46]:
# Automating the Data Cleaning section

# Loop through all columns
for col in df_tel.columns:
    # Display column name
    print()
    print(col)
    # Display whether it has null values
    print("Null :", "True" if sum(df_tel.loc[:, col].isnull()) else "False")
    
    # Check if column is currently assigned to int or float
    if df_tel.loc[:, col].dtype in ['int64', 'float64']:
        # Display the fact that the column is numeric
        print("Numeric assigned : True")
        
        # Check if column has a very few unique values
        if len(np.unique(df_tel.loc[:, col])) < 10:
            # Display the fact that the column is categoric
            print("Numeric actually: False")
            
            # Since Assigned datatype and the condition of that datatype do not match hence change data type to object
            df_tel.loc[:, col] = df_tel.loc[:, col].astype('object', errors='ignore')
            print("Column datatype has been changed to object type")
        
        # On condition that the column has a more than 10 unique values
        else:
            # Display the fact that the column is Numeric
            print("Numeric actually: True")
        # Display that the column is useful at first check
        print("Values are continous and hence useful")
    
    # On condition that the column is not int or float
    else:
        # Display the fact that the column is considered Categorical
        print("Numeric assigned : False")
        
        # Check if the categorical column is unique for every record
        if len(df_tel.iloc[:, 0].unique()) == df_tel.shape[0]:
            # Display the condition that the column is actually categorical
            print("Numeric actually: False")
            
            # Drop the column since every row is different from each other and it is categorical, hence useless
            df_tel.drop(col, inplace=True, axis=1)
            print("Column has been dropped since it unique for every value and hence useless")
            
        # Check if the categorical column has more than 100 different unique values
        elif len(np.unique(df_tel.loc[:, col])) > 100:
            
            # Display the fact that test has confirmed that the column is actually numeric
            print("Numeric actually: True")
            
            # Since Assigned datatype and the condition of that datatype do not match hence change data type to float64
            # Convert the highest frequency value to 0.0
            val = np.unique(df_tel.loc[:, col])[np.unique(df_tel.loc[:, col], return_counts=True)[1].argmax()]
            df_tel.loc[df_tel.loc[:, col] == val, col] = 0.0
            
            # Now the column is ready to converted to float datatype
            df_tel.loc[:, col] = df_tel.loc[:, col].astype('float64', errors='raise')
            print("Column datatype has been changed to float64 type")      
        
        # On condition that the categorical variable has few unique values
        else:
            # Display the fact that on test we think the column is categorical and useful
            print("Numeric actually: False")
            print("Values are categorical and useful")

There are some interesting points difference in the statistics from above. Let us verify whether these differences are significant
Before jumping into the test let us set our Null Hypothesis and Alternate Hypothesis.
Ho is (Churn = "Yes") = (Churn = "No")
Ha is (Churn = "Yes") (Churn = "No")
In [50]:
# Creating a function which will return required outputs after performing welch_ttest
def welch_ttest(x, y):
    ## Welch-Satterthwaite Degrees of Freedom ##
    dof = (x.var()/x.size + y.var()/y.size)**2 / ((x.var()/x.size)**2 / (x.size-1) + (y.var()/y.size)**2 / (y.size-1))
   
    # Welch's Test
    t, p = ttest_ind(x, y, equal_var = False)
    
    # Displaying the results found
    print("\n",
          f"Welch's t-test= {t:.4f}", "\n",
          f"p-value = {p:.4f}", "\n",
          f"Welch-Satterthwaite Degrees of Freedom= {dof:.4f}")
In [51]:
# Performing Welch's t test on Churn(Yes) and others groups for all continous independent variables
# Running a for loop to extract each continous attribute name individually
for col in list(df_tel.select_dtypes(include=['int64','float64']).columns):
    # Creating a 2 groups based on Dependent variable labels Normal and Abnormal (Type_H and Type_S)
    group1 = df_tel[col][df_tel["Churn"]=="Yes"]
    group2 = df_tel[col][df_tel["Churn"]!="Yes"]
    
    # Printing newline for cosmetic purposes
    print("\n", col)
    
    # If Shapiro test clears both groups (Confidence of 95%) then perform welch test else display appropriate message
    if (shapiro(group1)[1]<0.05) and (shapiro(group2)[1]<0.05):
        welch_ttest(group1, group2)
    else:
        print("\n At least one of the classes (Yes or No) is not normally distributed")

In [53]:
for col in list(df_tel.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns)[:-1]:
    crosstab = pd.crosstab(df_tel['Churn'], df_tel[col])
    chi, p_value, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(crosstab)
    print(col, "p - ", p_value)
    if p_value < 0.05:  # Setting our significance level at 5%
        print('{} Rejecting Null Hypothesis. \n There is significant difference in {} Feature for different category of target variable(Churn)'.format('\033[1m', col))
    else:
        print('{} Fail to Reject Null Hypothesis.\n There is no significant difference in {} Feature for different category of target variable(Churn)'.format('\033[1m', col))
    print('\n')

• Perform a detailed univariate, bivariate and multivariate analysis with appropriate detailed comments after each analysis.¶
Bi-variate Analysis
Let us first look at a property which caught my eye early on. One class called "No internet service" in the independent variables, is a weird property to classify. It must have meaning and we should understand it. I suspect this class is a result of a class in another column. To verify this we will check crosstabs against our culprit variable against all the other variables with this classify and see if there is a pattern.
Simply put a group of records will be clustered across all or some of the variables with the class "No internet service"
Assuming that the culprit variable is the column just before the column of the first occurence of "No internet service" we will check all columns with "No internet service" against column "InternetService"
In [54]:
# Creating a loop which will run through all columns with the class "No internet service"

    # Displaying the cross tab of each column against InternetService column
    print(pd.crosstab(df_tel.loc[:, "InternetService"], df_tel.loc[:, col]))
    print()

Univariate Analysis for outliers in continous variables
In [58]:
# Looping through all continous features
for col in list(df_tel.select_dtypes(include=['int64','float64']).columns):
    # Display Univariate analysis, Histogram and Boxplot
    f, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(17,7))
    sns.boxplot(x = col, data=df_tel,  orient='h' , ax=axes[1])
    sns.histplot(df_tel[col],  ax=axes[0])
    axes[0].set_title('Distribution plot')
    axes[1].set_title('Box plot')
    plt.show()
    
    # checking count of outliers.
    q25, q75 = np.percentile(df_tel[col], 25), np.percentile(df_tel[col], 75)
    IQR = q75-q25
    threshold=IQR*1.5
    lower, upper = q25 - threshold, q75 + threshold
    outliers = [i for i in df_tel[col] if i < lower or i > upper]
    print('{} Total Number of outliers in {}: {}'.format('\033[1m', col, len(outliers)))

X_train, y_train = sm.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

• Check if the train and test data have similar statistical characteristics when compared with original data.¶
The train and test data intentionally does not have similar statistical characteristics when it comes to target variable since we have applied SMOTE on train data only. However, splitting was done at 75% to 25% of original data. Also we dropped 1526 data based on Inference 2. Which means that the test set should be 25% of 5517. Which is approximately equal to test set total of 1380. Now in Test set we have 445 Yes, which is about 32% of the total set. Which is similar to original data set after 1526 data points were removed.
In [69]:

print("Proportion of Churn(Yes) in test set ", sum(y_test)/len(y_test))

5. Model training, testing and tuning: [ Score: 15 point ]¶

• Train and test all ensemble models taught in the learning module.¶
Instead of looking at the generic versions of all models we will Tune the models and do a grid search to try to focus on the best hyperparameters
• Apply all the possible tuning techniques to train the best model for the given data.¶
We will combine this question and the next because using all the possible hyper parameter combinations and tuning best model overlapped.
It is very important to note that we will use precision as our primary metric to determine best fit. This is because we would rather predict Churn and get it right than any other possibilities, because of the cost of getting Churn wrong.
• Suggestion: Use all possible hyper parameter combinations to extract the best accuracies.¶
Tuning max depth
In [70]:
###### GridSearchCV to find optimal n_estimators
#from sklearn.model_selection import KFold

# specify number of folds for k-fold CV
n_folds = 5

# parameters to build the model on
parameters = {'max_depth': range(2, 250, 30)}

# instantiate the model
rf = RandomForestClassifier()

# Set the metrics for evaluation
scoring = ['precision', 'accuracy','f1_macro']

# fit tree on training data
rf = GridSearchCV(rf, parameters, 
                    cv=n_folds, 
                   scoring=scoring,
                 refit='accuracy')
rf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# hyperparameter tuning with XGBoost

# creating a KFold object 
folds = 5

# specify range of hyperparameters
param_grid = {'learning_rate': [0.15, 0.2], 
             'subsample': [0.3, 0.6, 0.9],
              "max_depth": range(92, 123, 15),
              'n_estimators': [700, 800, 900],
              'reg_alpha': [0.1, 10]
             }          


# specify model
XGB = XGBClassifier(use_label_encoder=False, reg_lambda=0, random_state=42)

# set up GridSearchCV()
grid_search_XGB = GridSearchCV(estimator = XGB, 
                        param_grid = param_grid, 
                        scoring= scoring, 
                        cv = folds, 
                        verbose = 1,
                        return_train_score=True,
                        refit="accuracy")

In [115]:
# Builiding a function that will return the metrics
# Take the model, train data and test data as input
def fit_n_print(model, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test):
    
    # Note the start time
    start = time.time() 

    # Fit the model using the train data
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # Predictions on the test data based on the model
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    
    # Note the end time for the model
    end = time.time()

    # Display the confusion matrix between test and prediction
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    print(cm)
    
    # Calculate the overall accuracy   
    accuracy = sum(cm.diagonal())/cm.sum()  
    
    # Calculate the precision for No
    precision_no = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=0)
    
    # Calculate the precision for Yes
    precision_yes = precision_score(y_test, y_pred)
    
    # Calculate the recall for No
    recall_no = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=0)
    
    # Calculate the recall for Yes
    recall_yes = recall_score(y_test, y_pred)
    
    # Calculate the Area Under the Curve
    AUC = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred)
    
    # Calculate the runtime of the model
    duration = end - start
    
    # Return all evaluated metrics
    return(accuracy, precision_yes, recall_yes, AUC, precision_no, recall_no, duration) # return all the metrics along with predictions

In [118]:
def fit_prob_agg(model, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test):
    # Fit the model using the train data
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # Predictions on the test data based on the model
    y_pred = model.predict_proba(X_test)
    return(y_pred.T[0], y_pred.T[1])

• Select the final best trained model along with your detailed comments for selecting this model.¶
Selecting XGBoost as the best Model because it gave the best precision. As mentioned earlier we are focussing on isolating Churn clients instead of focussing on accuracy. Apart from Gradient Boosting all other models the highest accuracy and highest precision coincided on the same hyper parameters.
We tried and were hoping that hard voting based on the highest probability between all the models would give significantly better results than individual models but it did not. So we go with XGBoost as our final model.

# Creating a function which runs on Predict button left click event
def get_data(event):
    
    # Freeze button while get_data function is being executed
    predict["state"] = DISABLED
    
    # Define global variables since these will be needed in the main script as well
    global df_gui
    global pred_data
    
    # Initialising an empty dictionary for pred_data
    pred_data={}
    # Initialising a counter to go through all combo buttons
    idx=0
    
    # A loop to collect all categorical data given by user
    for col in list(df_tel.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns)[:-1]:
        pred_data[str(col+'_'+cb[idx].get())] = 1
        idx+=1
    
    # Initialising a counter to go through all slider inputs
    idx=0
    
    # A loop to collect all continous data given by user
    for col in list(df_tel.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64']).columns):
        pred_data[col] = slider[idx].get()
        idx+=1
    
    # Create and organise data in the form of X_test or how model has learnt to recieve data
    df_gui = pd.DataFrame(columns=X_train.columns)
    df_gui = pd.concat([df_gui, pd.DataFrame(pred_data, index=range(1))], axis=0).loc[:, X_train.columns].fillna(0)
    
    # Predict and convert output to No or Yes
    pred = 'No' if pickle_clf.predict(df_gui)==0 else 'Yes'
    
    # Paste prediction in textbox
    result['state']=NORMAL
    result.delete(0.0, 'end')
    result.insert(0.0, pred)
    result['state']=DISABLED
    
    # Unfreeze Predict button
    predict['state']=NORMAL
    
    return()

y = 50

# Place the Combobox widgets based on all categorical data
for col in list(df_tel.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns)[:-1]:
    ls_col = df_tel[col].unique()
    
    # Label
    txt = ttk.Label(window, text = "Select the "+col+" :", font = ("Times New Roman", 10))
    data = tuple(ls_col)
    cb.append(tk.ttk.Combobox(window, values=data))
    txt.place(x=x, y=y-22)
    cb[-1].place(x=x, y=y)
    if x+200<400:
        x+=200
    else:
        x=10
        y+=70
    cb[-1].current(0)

# Reinitialise position values and slider list
x=410
y=50
slider = []

# Place the Slider widgets based on all continous data
for col in list(df_tel.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64']).columns)[:-1]:

    txt.place(x=x, y=y-22)
    
    to = math.ceil(df_tel[col].max()/10)*10
    tickinterval = (to - 0)/10
    slider.append(Scale(window, from_=0, to=to, tickinterval=to/(to/10), length=230))
    slider[-1].set(round(df_tel[col].mean()/10)*10)
    slider[-1].place(x=x, y=y)
    y+=270

7. Conclusion and improvisation: [ Score: 5 point ]¶

• Write your conclusion on the results.¶
Combining this question and the next for my convenience
• Detailed suggestions or improvements or on quality, quantity, variety, velocity, veracity etc. on the data points collected by the telecom operator to perform a better data analysis in future.¶
The results have been challenged by time. No brilliant Machine Learning progress has been able to slow down time or have they managed in the form of best efficiency, stopped time. This project also has been challenged by the inevitable. We tried to use the highest probability as means to get better predictions, if we had time we would have tried Stacking ensemble model. At this point we are confident that we got the best precision (which was our focus). We can still improve our precision by using probability and using a higher probability than 50% to get better precision results. Here we would like to know the opinions of the client. We would like to know the cost of pursuing a Churn client in case they do not churn. This will help us quantify the precision results better.
